book-text-manual-artillery-mortar = Instructional guide on the proper usage of mortar systems

      To assemble your mortar, place the mortar assembly on the ground, and use the wrench included in your box of utilities to assemble the mortar.
      Use the wrench on the finished mortar to disassemble it.

      To fire your mortar, first insert a shell, then right click to open the context menu and click open mortar UI
      The X axis is east and west, positive numbers go east, negative numbers go west.
      The Y axis is north and south, positive numbers go north, negative numbers go south.

      Using your rangefinder included in the utilities box, you can find the range between yourself and your target


      How to find your firing solution with GPS coordinates

      find the coordinates of your mortar, for this example, lets say your mortar is at 22, -2
      find the coordinates of your target, lets say they are 25, 4
      grab your calculator, and subtract your target coordinates from your mortar's coordinates, in this example the result would be -3, -6
      determine if your target is roughly east or west, and north or south of your mortar. You can determine this by cross referencing your mortar and target coordinates and seeing if they are higher or lower
      after you determine your target's general direction, put the values in your mortar. For this example the target was north east of the mortar, meaning the X and Y coordinates should be positive, so the final firing solution would be 3, 6

      
      Pre-sighting and offsets
      
      It is a good idea to pre-sight targets, in order to set up an ambush or begin firing at a target without having to re-calculate. Inside your utility box will be a folder and pen for writing your calculations down.

      Once you have a known firing position (such as a friendly spotter) then you can start thinking about offsets
      Say you have a spotter, at -93, 100, and you already have the firing solution for those coordinates, being 15, -10 (Coordinates in this format are always X, Y)
      He calls out to you "Fire on my position, offset 5 meters north", simply increase your Y offset by 5, the end result being 15, -5


